And the wall collapsed ...
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best, and which one had the greatest impact on the planet?
a) The bloody suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) Elections in Poland
Few respond with option c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarność in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe—and therefore to the reconstruction of the postwar international order.
In the coming months, there will be all sorts of commemorations marking the end of communism, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc since the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a point of no return, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
He had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader in charge of Poland, General Jaruzelski, assessed that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to face alone.
"Why not call on the Polish opposition," he said, "—if not to find a solution— at least to share the responsibility for the situation?"
After six months of negotiations, he reached a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be able to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarność) never for a single moment considered that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they never imagined they would be driven from power.
Yet that is what happened.
Looking back, it's surprising that there could have been doubts.
Solidarność campaigned with audacity.
A commemorative poster, creatively reworked for the occasion, of a classic western film, "The Man Who Would Be King," achieved great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
On June 4th was the day of the Last Judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was about to give birth to summer, the voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversity that turned into an involuntary self-embarrassment.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to strike out the names of those they did not want—effectively all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long awaited, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared a state of martial law, banned Solidarity, and imprisoned its leaders.
The revolution by the pen!
Handled with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious vengeance.
Some voters tore up their ballots outright, thus effectively cutting off the old regime with a decisive blow.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing names off the lists.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Hey, that apparatchik got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
On the contrary, the communist campaign barely made a noticeable impact.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most of them relied on the monopoly they had over the media to spread their message: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
One can say to his credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable leniency.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials and declared: "Our defeat is total," we need to find a political solution."
It meant that he wanted neither violence nor fraud, and the communists would have to live with the result of the election.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us who covered Eastern Europe knew that Solidarity was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anticommunists all over the world.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, the Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected along the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "common European house" and rejected the interventionist doctrine of Brezhnev.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom broke out.
